Q1. What is the average career length of a cricketer?
Most cricketers have careers between 8–12 years. Long careers are relatively rare.

Q2. Do long-career players have higher strike rates?
Not necessarily. Long-career players usually maintain steady strike rates, while short careers show more variation.

Q3. How many players started before 1960?
Only a small number of players began their careers before 1960.

Q4. Which country has the highest individual scores?
A few countries dominate the top individual innings scores.

Q5. Which country averages the most centuries per player?
Countries with longer Test history tend to average more centuries per player.

Q6. Is there a relationship between career length and batting average?
Longer careers generally show stable batting averages. Short careers often show extreme values due to small sample size.

Q7. How is strike rate distributed?
Most players fall in the 40–70 strike rate range, typical for Test cricket.

Q8. Do more innings lead to a higher strike rate?
No strong relationship found. Strike rate depends more on playing style than experience.
